author = "R.A. Khan and J. Thulin",
abstract = "Publisher Summary Pollutants are being discharged continuously into the aquatic environment, and there is increasing concern about their impact on the ecosystem. Some major long-term threats to the aquatic biota are chronic pollution in estuarine and coastal areas originating from the land, and oil spills and seeps from tankers and drilling rigs offshore. A pollutant acting alone might not necessarily be harmful but in combination with others could induce stress. During the past decade, it has been increasingly clear that several fish diseases and abnormalities occur with increased prevalence in wild fish populations in highly polluted areas. While it has been difficult to relate concentrations of specific pollutants in water and sediments directly to disease, there are indications of such a connection in some organisms. Thus, pollutants might influence, directly or indirectly, the prevalence, intensity, and pathogenicity of a parasite. This chapter reviews present knowledge of this relationship. In attempting to do so, it examines how some different aquatic pollutants enter and affect the fish, which constitute the microhabitat of the parasites. It also describes a series of published and unpublished studies concerned with the influence of pollutants on ecto- and endoparasites of aquatic organisms. It provides suggestions for areas in need of further research. "
}

